          "body": "The vision of verses 13-17 is surrounded by darkness. Verse 18 begins with the chapter's harshest 'But' — and the images that follow are not countered. A mountain crumbles; a rock moves; water wears away stone; torrents wash away soil. Each of these is gradual, patient, inevitable — and Job transfers each to God's action against man: 'So You destroy man's hope' (v. 19). The same *tiqvah* (hope) that appeared in verse 7 as the tree's advantage is now explicitly destroyed. God 'forever overpowers' man (*netsach*, perpetuity, v. 20), changes his countenance, and sends him away. The chapter's final image is the absolute isolation of the dead: the departed man does not know if his sons are honored or disgraced (v. 21); he feels only his own bodily pain and mourns only for himself (v. 22). This is not Job's final word on resurrection — chapter 19 will recover the hope — but it is his honest report of where faith stands at this moment in the valley. The chapter does not resolve; it oscillates. That oscillation is itself a form of theological honesty."
