          "title": "Job 14 in canonical perspective — a seed of resurrection",
          "body": "Job 14:14 — 'If a man dies, will he live again?' — is the Old Testament's most direct wrestling with bodily resurrection. The question is not rhetorical dismissal; it is voiced hope pressing against apparent impossibility. Job does not yet have the Pauline vocabulary of 1 Corinthians 15 or the synoptic accounts of the empty tomb, but he is reaching for exactly what those texts confirm. Interpreters in the Reformed tradition (Calvin, Owen) read the passage as genuine Spirit-given anticipation of resurrection beyond what Job's natural knowledge could supply — the same Spirit who inspired David to speak of the Holy One not seeing decay (Ps. 16:10, cited in Acts 2:27). The tree-stump image anticipates Isaiah 11:1 (the shoot from the stump of Jesse) and the broader Old Testament pattern of life-from-death. The 'longing' of God for the work of His hands (v. 15) connects to the New Testament's declaration that God 'so loved the world' (John 3:16) — the Creator's desire for His creature does not terminate at the grave. Job 14 plants a seed that the rest of the canon waters until the full flower appears in the resurrection of Jesus Christ."
